\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Singular Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Standard Simplicies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{0},\dots,v_{n}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 such that the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}-v_{0},\dots,v_{n}-v_{0}$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series bold
-simplex 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is the smallest convex set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{0},\dots,v_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
vertices 
\series default
of the simplex.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series bold
-dimensional standard simplex 
\series default
is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta^{n}:=\left\{ (t_{0},\dots,t_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid t_{i}\in[0,1]\text{ and \ensuremath{\sum t_{i}=1}}\right\} =[e_{0},\dots,e_{n}],
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the standard coordinate vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}=(0,\dots,1,\dots,0)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 everywhere else).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For purposes of homology it will be important to keep track of the order
 of the vertices of a simplex, so 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will really mean 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex with an ordering of its vertices
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Specifying the ordering of the vertices also determines a canonical linear
 homeomorphism from the standard 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 onto any other 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

, preserving the order of vertices, namely, 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{0},\dots,t_{n})\mapsto\sum_{i}t_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\series bold
barycentric coordinates 
\series default
of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}t_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Delta Complex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset


\series bold
-complex 
\series default
structure on a space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a collection of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha}\colon\Delta^{n}\to X$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 depending on the index 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha}|_{\Delta^{n}\backslash\partial\Delta^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is injective, and each point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is in the image of exactly one such restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha}|_{\Delta^{n}\backslash\partial\Delta^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Each restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 to a face of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 is one of the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\beta}\colon\Delta^{n-1}\to X$
\end_inset

.
 Here we are identifying the face of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 by the canonical linear homeomorphism betweem them that preserves the ordering
 of the vertices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha}^{-1}(A)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among other things, this last condition rules out trivialities like regarding
 all the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are individual vertices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Singular Homology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 A continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon\Delta^{n}\to X$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
singular
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series bold
-simplex in
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 A continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}\colon[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]\to X$
\end_inset

 determines a unique continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon\Delta^{n}\to X$
\end_inset

 via the canonical linear homeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 as a singular 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex via 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 We frequently use this convention without comment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The set 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 and the free abelian group with basis the set of singular 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X):=\mathbb{Z}[\Sigma_{n}(X)]$
\end_inset

.
 Elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
singular 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series bold
-chains
\series default
.
 We also denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma(X):=\bigcup_{n}\Sigma_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 a ring.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{n}(X;R):=\bigoplus_{\sigma\in\Sigma_{n}(X)}R\quad\text{and}\quad S(X;R):=\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}S_{n}(X;R),
\]

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $S(X;R)$
\end_inset

 is a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module whose 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th homogeneous piece is the free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X;R)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{R}\colon S(X;R)\to S(X;R)$
\end_inset

 be the unique graded endomorphism of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 such that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\Sigma_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{R}(\sigma)=\sum_{i}(-1)^{i}\sigma_{|[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots,e_{n}]},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots,e_{n}]=[e_{0},\dots,e_{i-1},e_{i+1}\dots,e_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 By a direct calculation, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{R}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

: Indeed
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{R}^{2}(\sigma) & =\partial_{R}\left(\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}\sigma_{|[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots,e_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}\partial_{R}\left(\sigma_{|[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots,e_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}\left(\sum_{0\leq j<i}(-1)^{j}\sigma_{|[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{j},\dots\widehat{e}_{i},\dots e_{n}]}+\sum_{i<j\leq n}(-1)^{j+1}\sigma_{|[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots\widehat{e}_{j},\dots e_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq j<i\leq n}(-1)^{i+j}\sigma_{|[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{j},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots e_{n}]}+\sum_{0\leq i<j\leq n}(-1)^{i+j+1}\sigma_{|[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots,\widehat{e}_{j},\dots e_{n}]}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(S(X;R),\partial_{R})$
\end_inset

 forms a chain complex over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

; it is called the 
\series bold
singular
\series default
 
\series bold
chain complex of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th homology of 
\begin_inset Formula $(S(X;R),\partial_{R})$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series bold
th singular homology of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
over 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}^{\text{sing}}(X;R)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to A$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism, then we change our base ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A\otimes_{R}S_{n}(X;R) & \cong A\otimes_{R}\left(\bigoplus_{\sigma\in\Sigma_{n}(X)}R\right)\\
 & \cong\bigoplus_{\sigma\in\Sigma_{n}(X)}(A\otimes_{R}R)\\
 & \cong\bigoplus_{\sigma\in\Sigma_{n}(X)}A\\
 & =S_{n}(X;A).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A\otimes_{R}S(X;R) & =A\otimes_{R}\left(\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}}S_{n}(X;R)\right)\\
 & \cong\bigoplus_{n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}}A\otimes_{R}S_{n}(X;R)\\
 & \cong S(X;A),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $A\otimes_{R}(S(X;R),\partial_{R})\cong(S(X;A),\partial_{A})$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $A\otimes_{R}H_{\text{sing}}^{n}(X;R)\cong H_{\text{sing}}^{n}(X;A)$
\end_inset

.
 If the base ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is understood from context, then we usually simplify notation by removing
 the label 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 .
 For instance, we often replace 
\begin_inset Formula $S(X;R)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S(X)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}^{\text{sing}}(X;R)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}^{\text{sing}}(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Reduced Homology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is often very convenient to have a slightly modified version of homology
 for which a point has trivial homology groups in all dimensions, including
 zero.
 This is done by defining the 
\series bold
reduced homology groups 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{H}_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to be the homology groups of the augmented chain complex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] & S_2 (X)  
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
partial _2 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & S_1 (X)  
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
partial _1 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & S_0 (X) 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
varepsilon 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & R 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 sits in degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\left(\sum_{i}r_{i}\sigma_{i}\right)=\sum_{i}r_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Here we had better require 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to be nonempty in order to avoid a nontrivial homology group in dimension
 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\partial_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 vanishes on 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Im}(\partial_{1})$
\end_inset

 and hence induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}(X)\to\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{H}_{0}(X)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}(X)\cong\widetilde{H}_{0}(X)\oplus R$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}(X)=\widetilde{H}_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homotopy Invariance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\#}\colon S(X)\to S(Y)$
\end_inset

 to be the unique graded homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules such 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\#}(\sigma)=f\circ\sigma$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\Sigma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\#}$
\end_inset

 is more than just a graded homomorphism: it is a chain map.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\Sigma_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial f_{\#}(\sigma) & =\partial(f\circ\sigma)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}(f\circ\sigma)|_{[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots,e_{n}]}\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}\left(f\circ\sigma|_{[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots,e_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =f_{\#}\left(\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}\sigma|_{[e_{0},\dots,\widehat{e}_{i},\dots,e_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =f_{\#}\partial(\sigma).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It is easy to check that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon Y\to Z$
\end_inset

 are continuous maps, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(f\circ g)_{\#}=f_{\#}\circ g_{\#}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have a covariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $F\colon\mathbf{Top}\to\mathbf{Chain}_{R}$
\end_inset

 from the category of topoligical spaces to the category of chain complexes
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, given by mapping a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the chain complex 
\begin_inset Formula $S(X)$
\end_inset

 and mapping a continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 to the chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\#}\colon S(X)\to S(Y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be continuous functions and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are homotopically equivalent as continuous functions.
 Then the chain maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\#}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\#}$
\end_inset

 are homotopically equivalent as chain maps.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The essential ingredient is a procedure for subdividing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times I$
\end_inset

 into simplices.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times\{0\}=[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times\{1\}=[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 have the same image under the projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times I\to\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We can pass from 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

 by interpolating a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices, each obtained from the preceding one by moving one vertex 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

, starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n}$
\end_inset

 and working backwards to 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the first step is to move 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n-1},w_{n}]$
\end_inset

, then the second step is to move this up to 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n-2},w_{n-1},w_{n}]$
\end_inset

, and so on.
 In the typical step 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i+1},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

 moves up to 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{i-1},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 The region between these two 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices is exactly the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

 which has 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i+1},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

 as its lower face and 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{i-1},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

 as its upper face.
 Altogether, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times I$
\end_inset

 is the union of 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)$
\end_inset

-simplices 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

, each intersecting the next in an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex face.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given a homotopy 
\begin_inset Formula $H\colon X\times I\to Y$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and a singular simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon\Delta^{n}\to X$
\end_inset

, we can form the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $H\circ(\sigma\times1)\colon\Delta^{n}\times I\to X\times I\to Y$
\end_inset

.
 Using this, we can define 
\series bold
prism operators 
\begin_inset Formula $P\colon S_{n}(X)\to S_{n+1}(Y)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
by the following formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\sigma)=\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]}.
\]

\end_inset

We will show that these prism operators satisfy the formula 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial P=g_{\#}-f_{\#}-P\partial.
\]

\end_inset

Geometrically, the left side of this equation represents the boundary of
 the prism, and the three terms on the right side represent the top 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times\{1\}$
\end_inset

, the bottom 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times\{0\}$
\end_inset

, and the sides 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Delta^{n}\times I$
\end_inset

 of the prism.
 To prove the relation, we calculate
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial P(\sigma) & =\partial\left(\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}\partial\left(H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i}\left(\sum_{0\leq j\leq i}(-1)^{j}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,\widehat{v}_{j},\dots v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]}+\sum_{i\leq j\leq n}(-1)^{j+1}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,\widehat{w}_{j},\dots,w_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq j\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i+j}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,\widehat{v}_{j},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]}+\sum_{0\leq j\leq i\leq n}(-1)^{i+j+1}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,\widehat{w}_{j},\dots,w_{n}]}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The terms 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

 in the two sums cancel except for 
\begin_inset Formula $H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]}$
\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ\sigma=g_{\#}(\sigma)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $-H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]}$
\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $-f\circ\sigma=-f_{\#}(\sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 The terms with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 are exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $-P\partial(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P\partial(\sigma) & =P\left(\sum_{0\leq j\leq n}(-1)^{j}\sigma|_{[v_{0},\dots,\widehat{v}_{j},\dots,v_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq j\leq n}(-1)^{j}P\left(\sigma|_{[v_{0},\dots,\widehat{v}_{j},\dots,v_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq j\leq n}(-1)^{j}\left(\sum_{0\leq i<j}(-1)^{i}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,\widehat{w}_{j},\dots,w_{n}]}+\sum_{j<i\leq n}(-1)^{i+1}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,\widehat{v}_{j},\dots v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i<j\leq n}(-1)^{i+j}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,\widehat{w}_{j},\dots,w_{n}]}+\sum_{0\leq j<i\leq n}(-1)^{i+j+1}H\circ(\sigma\times1)|_{[v_{0},\dots,\widehat{v}_{j},\dots,v_{i},w_{i},\dots,w_{n}]}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a homotopy from 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\#}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\#}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are homotopically equivalent as continuous functions, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\#}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\#}$
\end_inset

 induce the same map on homology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exact Sequences and Excision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $A\hookrightarrow X$
\end_inset

 induces a chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $(S(A),\partial)\hookrightarrow(S(X),\partial)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(S(X,A),\overline{\partial})$
\end_inset

 denote the cokernel of this map.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $S(X,A)$
\end_inset

 is the graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $S(X)/S(A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}$
\end_inset

 is the boundary map induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

.
 The homology of 
\begin_inset Formula $(S(X,A),\partial)$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
relative homology 
\series default
and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $H(X,A)$
\end_inset

.
 By considering the definition of the relative boundary map we see that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}(X,A)$
\end_inset

 are represented by 
\series bold
relative cycles
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-chains 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\alpha\in S_{n-1}(A)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A relative cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is trivial in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}(X,A)$
\end_inset

 if and only if it is a 
\series bold
relative boundary
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\partial\beta+\gamma$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in S_{n+1}(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in S_{n}(A)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X)/S_{n}(A)$
\end_inset

 could also be viewed as a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

, the subgroup with basis the singular 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon\Delta^{n}\to X$
\end_inset

 whose image is not contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 However, the boundary map does not take this subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 to the corresponding subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n-1}(X)$
\end_inset

, so it is usually better to regard 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X,A)$
\end_inset

 as a quotient rather than a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the long exact sequence of reduced homology groups for the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(D^{n},\partial D^{n})$
\end_inset

, the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}(D^{n},\partial D^{n})\to\widetilde{H}_{i-1}(S^{n-1})$
\end_inset

 are isomorphisms for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i>0$
\end_inset

 since the remaining terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{H}_{i}(D^{n})$
\end_inset

 are zero for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we obtain the calculation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{i}(D^{n},\partial D^{n})\cong\begin{cases}
\mathbb{Z} & \text{if }i=n\\
0 & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Applying the long exact sequence of reduced homology groups to a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,x_{0})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

 yields isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}(X,x_{0})\cong\widetilde{H}_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{H}_{n}(x_{0})\cong0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Excision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given subspaces 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subset A\subset X$
\end_inset

 such that the closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is contained in the interior of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash Z,A\backslash Z)\hookrightarrow(X,A)$
\end_inset

 induces isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}(X\backslash Z,A\backslash Z)\to H_{n}(X,A)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, for subspaces 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subset X$
\end_inset

 whose interiors cover 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $(B,A\cap B)\hookrightarrow(X,A)$
\end_inset

 induces isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}(B,A\cap B)\to H_{n}(X,A)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The translation between the two versions is obtained by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $B=X\backslash Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=X\backslash B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=A\backslash Z$
\end_inset

 and the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Z}\subset\text{int}(A)$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\text{int}(A)\cup\text{int}(B)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash\text{int}(B)=\overline{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For a spae 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}=\{U_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 whose interiors form an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 consisting of chains 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}r_{i}\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 has image contained in some set in the cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

.
 The boundary map 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 takes 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

, so the groups 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

 form a chain complex.
 We denote the homology groups of this chain complex by 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\hookrightarrow S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 is a chain homotopy equivalence, that is, there is a chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\colon S_{n}(X)\to S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\iota$
\end_inset

 are chain homotopic to the identity.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 induces isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\cong H_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The barycentric subdivision process will be performed at four levels, beginning
 with the most geometric and becoming increasingly algebraic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(1) 
\series default
Barycentric Subdivision of Simplices: The points of a simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 are the linear combinations 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}t_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum t_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
barycenter 
\series default
or 'center of gravity' of the simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is the point 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\sum t_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

 whose barycentric coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 are all equal, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}=1/(n+1)$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
barycentric subdivision 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is the decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 into the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices 
\begin_inset Formula $[b,w_{0},\dots,w_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 where, inductively, 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},\dots,w_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-simplex in the barycentric subdivision of a face 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,\widehat{v}_{i},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 The induction starts with the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 when the barycentric subdivision of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0}]$
\end_inset

 is defined to be just 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0}]$
\end_inset

 itself.
 It follows from the inductive definition that the vertices of simplices
 in the barycentric subdivision of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 are exactly the barycenters of all the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-dimensional faces 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{i_{0}},\dots,v_{i_{k}}]$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 this gives the original vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 since the barycenter of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-simplex is itself.
 The barycenter of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{i_{0}},\dots,v_{i_{k}}]$
\end_inset

 has barycentric coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}=1/(k+1)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=i_{0},\dots,i_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices of the barycentric subdivision of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

, together with all their faces, do in fact form a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

-complex structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

, indeed a simplicial complex structure, though we shall not need to know
 this in what follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A fact we will need is that the diameter of each simplex of the barycentric
 subdivision of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

 times the diameter of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Here the diameter of a simplex is by definition the maximum distance between
 any two of its points, and we are using the metric from the ambient Euclidean
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 The diameter of a simplex equals the maximum distance between any of its
 vertices because the distance between the points 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum t_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 satisfies the inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|v-\sum_{i=0}^{n}t_{i}v_{i}\right|| & =\left|\sum_{i=0}^{n}t_{i}(v-v_{i})\right|\\
 & \leq\sum_{i=0}^{n}t_{i}|v-v_{i}|\\
 & \leq\sum_{i=0}^{n}t_{i}\max_{0\leq j\leq n}|v-v_{j}|\\
 & =\max_{0\leq j\leq n}|v-v_{j}|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The significance of the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

 is that by repeated barycentric subdivision we can produce simplices of
 arbitrarily small diameter since 
\begin_inset Formula $(n/(n+1))^{r}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 goes to infinity.
 It is important that the bound 
\begin_inset Formula $n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

 does not depend on the shape of the simplex since repeated barycentric
 subdivision produces simplices of many different shapes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To obtain the bound 
\begin_inset Formula $n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

 on the ratio of diameters, we therefore need to verify that the distance
 between any two vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{k}$
\end_inset

 of a simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

 of the barycentric subdivision of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n/(n+1)$
\end_inset

 times the diameter of 
\begin_inset Formula $[v_{0},\dots,v_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(2) 
\series default
Barycentric Subdivision of Linear Chains.
 The main part of the proof will be to construct a subdivision operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\colon S_{n}(X)\to S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 and show that this is chain homotopic to the identity map.
 First we will construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 and the chain homotopy in a more restricted linear setting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For a convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 in some Euclidean space, the linear maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\to Y$
\end_inset

 generate a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(Y)$
\end_inset

 that we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{n}(Y)$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
linear chains
\series default
.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $L(Y)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

-stable, so the linear chains form a subcomplex of 
\begin_inset Formula $(S(Y),\partial)$
\end_inset

.
 We can uniquely designate a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\colon\Delta^{n}\to Y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the image under 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th vertex of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, by linearity we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(\sum t_{i}e_{i})=\sum t_{i}\lambda(e_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 To avoid having to make exceptions for 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-simplices, it will be convenient to augment the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $(L(Y),\partial)$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{-1}(Y)=R$
\end_inset

 generated by the empty simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $[\emptyset]$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial[w_{0}]=[\emptyset]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-simplices 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Each point 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in Y$
\end_inset

 determines a graded homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $b\colon L(Y)\to L(Y)$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, defined on basis elements by 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left([w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]\right)=[b,w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Geometrically, the homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 can be regarded as a cone operator, sending a linear chain to the cone
 having the linear chain as the base of the cone and the point 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as the tip of the cone.
 Applying the usual formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

, we obtain the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial b([w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]) & =\partial[b,w_{0},\dots,w_{n}])\\
 & =[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]-b(\partial[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

By linearity it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial b(\alpha)=\alpha-b(\partial\alpha)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 This expresses algebraically the geometric fact that the boundary of a
 cone consists of its base together with the cone on the boundary of its
 base.
 The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial b(\alpha)=\alpha-b(\partial\alpha)$
\end_inset

 can be rewritten as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial b+b\partial=1,
\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a chain homotopy between the identity map and the zero map of the augmented
 chain complex 
\begin_inset Formula $(L(Y),\partial)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we define a graded homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\colon L(Y)\to L(Y)$
\end_inset

 by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\colon\Delta^{n}\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a generator of 
\begin_inset Formula $L(Y)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 be the image of the barycenter of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inductive formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{S}(\lambda)=b_{\lambda}(\mathcal{S}(\partial\lambda)),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\lambda}\colon L(Y)\to L(Y)$
\end_inset

 is the cone operator defined in the preceding paragraph.
 The induction starts with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}([\emptyset])=[\emptyset]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 is the identity on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{-1}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 To get a feel for the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0}]\in L_{0}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{S}[w_{0}] & =w_{0}\left(\mathcal{S}(\partial[w_{0}])\right)\\
 & =w_{0}(\mathcal{S}[\emptyset])\\
 & =w_{0}[\emptyset]\\
 & =[w_{0}].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},w_{1}]\in L_{1}(Y)$
\end_inset

 with barycenter 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{01}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{S}[w_{0},w_{1}] & =b_{01}\left(\mathcal{S}(\partial[w_{0},w_{1}])\right)\\
 & =b_{01}(\mathcal{S}[w_{1}]-\mathcal{S}[w_{0}])\\
 & =b_{01}([w_{1}]-[w_{0}])\\
 & =[b_{01},w_{1}]-[b_{01},w_{0}].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},w_{1},w_{2}]\in L_{2}(Y)$
\end_inset

 with barycenter 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{012}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{S}[w_{0},w_{1},w_{2}] & =b_{012}\left(\mathcal{S}(\partial[w_{0},w_{1},w_{2}])\right)\\
 & =b_{012}(\mathcal{S}[w_{1},w_{2}]-\mathcal{S}[w_{0},w_{2}]+\mathcal{S}[w_{0},w_{1}])\\
 & =b_{012}([b_{12},w_{2}]-[b_{12},w_{1}]-[b_{02},w_{2}]+[b_{02},w_{0}]+[b_{01},w_{1}]-[b_{01},w_{0}])\\
 & =[b_{012},b_{12},w_{2}]-[b_{012},b_{12},w_{1}]+[b_{012},b_{02},w_{0}]-[b_{012},b_{02},w_{2}]+[b_{012},b_{01},w_{1}]-[b_{012},b_{01},w_{0}],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{12}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{02}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{01}$
\end_inset

 are the barycenters for the simplices 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{1},w_{2}]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},w_{2}]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},w_{1}]$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 In general, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an embedding, with image a genuine 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 is the sum of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices in the barycentric subdivision of 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},\dots,w_{n}]$
\end_inset

, with certain signs that could be computed explicitly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\colon L(Y)\to L(Y)$
\end_inset

 is a chain map, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathcal{S}=\mathcal{S}\partial$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}=1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{0}(Y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{-1}(Y)$
\end_inset

, we certainly have 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathcal{S}=\mathcal{S}\partial$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{0}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 The result for larger 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is given by the following calculation, in which we omit some parentheses
 to unclutter the formulas:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial\mathcal{S}\lambda & =\partial b_{\lambda}(\mathcal{S}\partial\lambda)\\
 & =(1-b_{\lambda}\partial)(\mathcal{S}\partial\lambda)\\
 & =\mathcal{S}\partial\lambda-b_{\lambda}\partial(\mathcal{S}\partial\lambda)\\
 & =\mathcal{S}\partial\lambda-b_{\lambda}\mathcal{S}(\partial\partial\lambda)\\
 & =\mathcal{S}\partial\lambda,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial S(\partial\lambda)=S\partial(\partial\lambda)$
\end_inset

 follows by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We next build a chain homotopy 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}\colon L(Y)\to L(Y)$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 and the identity.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{n}(Y)$
\end_inset

 inductively by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=-1$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}\lambda=b_{\lambda}(\lambda-\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 The induction starts with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}[\emptyset]=0$
\end_inset

.
 To get a feel for the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0}]\in L_{0}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{T}[w_{0}] & =w_{0}\left([w_{0}]-\mathcal{T}\partial[w_{0}]\right)\\
 & =w_{0}\left([w_{0}]-\mathcal{T}[\emptyset]\right)\\
 & =[w_{0},w_{0}].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $[w_{0},w_{1}]\in L_{1}(Y)$
\end_inset

 with barycenter 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{01}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{T}[w_{0},w_{1}] & =b_{01}\left([w_{0},w_{1}]-\mathcal{T}\partial[w_{0},w_{1}]\right)\\
 & =b_{01}\left([w_{0},w_{1}]-\mathcal{T}[w_{1}]+\mathcal{T}[w_{0}]\right)\\
 & =[b_{01},w_{0},w_{1}]-[b_{01},w_{1},w_{1}]+[b_{01},w_{0},w_{0}].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The geometric motivation for this formula is an inductively defined subdivision
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times I$
\end_inset

 obtained by joining all simplices in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times\{0\}\cup\partial\Delta^{n}\times I$
\end_inset

 to the barycenter of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 What 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 actually does is take the image of this subdivision under the projection
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}\times I\to\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The chain homotopy formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathcal{T}+\mathcal{T}\partial=1-\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 is trivial on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{-1}(Y)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Verifying the formula on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{n}(Y)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 is done by the calculation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial\mathcal{T}\lambda & =\partial b_{\lambda}(\lambda-\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda)\\
 & =(1-b_{\lambda}\partial)(\lambda-\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda)\\
 & =\lambda-\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda-b_{\lambda}\partial\lambda+b_{\lambda}\partial\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda\\
 & =\lambda-\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda-b_{\lambda}\partial\lambda+b_{\lambda}(1-\mathcal{S}-\mathcal{T}\partial)\partial\lambda\\
 & =\lambda-\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda-b_{\lambda}\partial\lambda+b_{\lambda}\partial\lambda-b_{\lambda}\mathcal{S}\partial\lambda-b_{\lambda}\mathcal{T}\partial\partial\lambda\\
 & =\lambda-\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda-b_{\lambda}\mathcal{S}\partial\lambda\\
 & =\lambda-\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda-\mathcal{S}\lambda.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathcal{T}\partial\lambda=(1-\mathcal{S}-\mathcal{T}\partial)\partial\lambda$
\end_inset

 follows by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Now we discard 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{-1}(Y)$
\end_inset

 and the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathcal{T}+\mathcal{T}\partial=1-\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 still holds since 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 was zero on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{-1}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(3) 
\series default
Barycentric Subdivision of General Chains.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\colon S_{n}(X)\to S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\sigma=\sigma_{\#}\mathcal{S}\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 for a singular 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon\Delta^{n}\to X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the sum of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices in the barycentric subdivision of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

, with certain signs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding signed sum of the restrictions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplices of the barycentric subdivision of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in S_{1}(X)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{S}\sigma & =\sigma_{\#}\mathcal{S}[e_{0},e_{1}]\\
 & =\sigma\circ\left([b,e_{1}]-[e_{0},b]\right)\\
 & =\sigma|_{[b,e_{1}]}-\sigma|_{[e_{0},b]},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b=(e_{0}+e_{1})/2$
\end_inset

 is the barycenter of 
\begin_inset Formula $[e_{0},e_{1}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 is a chain map since
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial\mathcal{S}\sigma & =\partial\sigma_{\#}\mathcal{S}\Delta^{n}\\
 & =\sigma_{\#}\partial\mathcal{S}\Delta^{n}\\
 & =\sigma_{\#}\mathcal{S}\partial\Delta^{n}\\
 & =\sigma_{\#}S(\sum_{i}(-1)^{i}\Delta_{i}^{n})\\
 & =\sum_{i}(-1)^{i}\sigma_{\#}S\Delta_{i}^{n}\\
 & =\sum_{i}(-1)^{i}S(\sigma|_{\Delta_{i}^{n}})\\
 & =S\left(\sum_{i}(-1)^{i}\sigma|_{\Delta_{i}^{n}}\right)\\
 & =S(\partial\sigma).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th face of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In similar fashion we define 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon S_{n}(X)\to S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $T\sigma=\sigma_{\#}T\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

, and this gives a chain homotopy between 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and the identity, since the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial T+T\partial=1-S$
\end_inset

 holds by the calculation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial T\sigma & =\partial\sigma_{\#}T\Delta^{n}\\
 & =\sigma_{\#}\partial T\Delta^{n}\\
 & =\sigma_{\#}(\Delta^{n}-S\Delta^{n}-T\partial\Delta^{n})\\
 & =\sigma-S\sigma-\sigma_{\#}T\partial\Delta^{n}\\
 & =\sigma-S\sigma-T(\partial\sigma)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last equality follows just as in the previous displayed calculation,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(4) 
\series default
Iterated Barycentric Subdivision.
 A chain homotopy between 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and the iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{m}$
\end_inset

 is given by the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{m}=\sum_{0\leq i<m}TS^{i}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial D_{m}+D_{m}\partial & =\sum_{0\leq i<m}(\partial TS^{i}+TS^{i}\partial)\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i<m}(\partial TS^{i}+T\partial S^{i})\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i<m}(\partial T+T\partial)S^{i}\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i<m}(1-S)S^{i}\\
 & =\sum_{0\leq i<m}(S^{i}-S^{i+1})\\
 & =1-S^{m}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For each singular 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon\Delta^{n}\to X$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{m}(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

 since the diameter of the simplices of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{m}(\Delta^{n})$
\end_inset

 will be less than a Lebesgue number of the cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 by the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-1}(\text{int}(U_{j}))$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is large enough.
 (Recall that a Lebesgue number for an open cover of a compact metric space
 is a number 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that every set of diameter less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 lies in some set of the cover; such a number exists by an elementary compactnes
s argument).
 We cannot expect the same number 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 to work for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

's, so let us define 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 to be the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{m}(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now define 
\begin_inset Formula $D\colon S_{n}(X)\to S_{n+1}(X)$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $D\sigma=D_{m(\sigma)}\sigma$
\end_inset

 for each singular 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon\Delta^{n}\to X$
\end_inset

.
 For this 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 we would like to find a chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\colon S_{n}(X)\to S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 with image in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

 satisfying the chain homotopy equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial D+D\partial=1-\rho.\label{eq:homotopyd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A quick way to do this is to simply regard this equation as defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, so we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1-\partial D-D\partial$
\end_inset

.
 It follows easily that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a chain map since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial\rho(\sigma) & =\partial\sigma-\partial^{2}D\sigma-\partial D\partial\sigma\\
 & =\partial\sigma-\partial D\partial\sigma\\
 & =\partial\sigma-\partial D\partial\sigma-D\partial^{2}\sigma\\
 & =\rho(\partial\sigma).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 takes 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

, we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 more explicitly:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho(\sigma) & =\sigma-\partial D\sigma-D(\partial\sigma)\\
 & =\sigma-\partial D_{m(\sigma)}(\partial\sigma)-D(\partial\sigma)\\
 & =S^{m(\sigma)}\sigma+D_{m(\sigma)}(\partial\sigma)-D(\partial\sigma).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The term 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{m(\sigma)}\sigma$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}(X)}$
\end_inset

 by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 The remaining terms 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{m(\sigma)}(\partial\sigma)-D(\partial\sigma)$
\end_inset

 are linear combinations of terms 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{m(\sigma)}(\sigma_{j})-D_{m(\sigma_{j})}(\sigma_{j})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{j}$
\end_inset

 the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to a face of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\sigma_{j})\leq m(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 and hence the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{m(\sigma)}(\sigma_{j})-D_{m(\sigma_{j})}(\sigma_{j})$
\end_inset

 consists of terms 
\begin_inset Formula $TS^{i}(\sigma_{j})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq m(\sigma_{j})$
\end_inset

, and these terms lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 takes 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n-1}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

View 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 as a chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}(X)\to S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

, the equation 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homotopyd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial D+D\partial=1-\iota\rho$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\hookrightarrow S_{n}(X)$
\end_inset

 the inclusion.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\iota=1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is identically zero on 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\sigma)=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{\mathcal{U}}(X)$
\end_inset

, hence the summation defining 
\begin_inset Formula $D\sigma$
\end_inset

 is empty.
 Thus we have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a chain homotopy inverse for 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

